          "body": "Zephaniah opens with one of the most startling first words in the prophetic canon: God announces He will 'completely remove all things from the face of the earth.' The Hebrew of verse 2 is an intensified infinitive absolute — 'removing I will remove,' a grammatical structure that intensifies the certainty and totality of the action. The list that follows — man, beast, birds, fish — deliberately reverses the order of Genesis 1. Creation came forth from God's word of blessing; here it is swept back by His word of judgment. This is not hyperbole but typological language: the coming Babylonian devastation is being read through the lens of the Flood (Genesis 6:7 uses nearly identical language), presenting it as a covenant-enforced de-creation. What God built up in creation and in covenant He is now prepared to sweep away when His image-bearers have defaced that image through idolatry. The opening two verses establish that the stakes of Judah's sin are not merely national but cosmological."
