          "body": "The chapter's final two verses deliver the verdict in absolute terms. Verse 17 gives the moral ground: 'because they have sinned against the LORD.' All the disasters catalogued in this chapter are not random catastrophe — they are the morally grounded response of a holy God to covenant sin. The images of judgment are visceral: blood poured out like dust, flesh scattered like dung — the humiliation of human bodies reduced to the status of worthless refuse. Then verse 18 closes the door on every escape route. Neither silver nor gold will deliver on that day. This directly addresses the merchant class of verse 11 and the wealthy of verse 13 who trusted in accumulated wealth. The very things Judah had substituted for God — material prosperity, economic security, accumulated power — are explicitly disqualified as saviors on the Day they are most needed. The final note is both the chapter's darkest and its most theologically revealing: 'the fire of His jealousy.' Jealousy (qinah) is the covenantal word — God's exclusive, protective, consuming passion for His people. The fire that will devour the earth is not random fury but the burning of a covenant God whose people have played the harlot with every neighboring deity. The destruction is, at its root, the response of a Husband who will not be abandoned."
